                                                                                                               Nirupama foreign secy
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Nirupama Rao                                  
	New Delhi, June 30: Nirupama Rao, Indias ambassador to Beijing, was today named the next foreign secretary. She will succeed Shiv Shankar Menon who retires on July 31.         
	Nirupama, a 1973-batch IFS officer, is the second woman to be appointed foreign secretary after Chokila Iyer who had a brief stint in 2001.         
	Nirupama was the first woman spokesperson for the ministry of external affairs.         
	A postgraduate in English literature, Nirupama topped the IFS in 1973 and joined the service at the age of 21. Lok Sabha speaker Meira Kumar, the Lok Sabhas first woman Speaker, was from the same IFS batch.         
	Nirupama has also served as Indian ambassador in Peru and Sri Lanka and as the deputy chief of mission in Moscow.         
	Jaisingh post        
	Lawyer Indira Jaisingh has been appointed Indias first woman additional solicitor-general, sources said.        
	Jaisingh is a noted Supreme Court lawyer and human rights activist.        
	The sources said her name had been cleared by the law ministry.                                                                                                                                                                           
